summary: @ Jon/Sansa fans please stop comparing the scene where Jon grabs Theon in 7.04 to the scene where he grabs Littlefinger. The...
body:
@ Jon/Sansa fans please stop comparing the scene where Jon grabs Theon in 7.04 to the scene where he grabs Littlefinger. The only similarity is the visual, the meaning behind those scenes is completely different. All the time I see both scenes paired together with some caption like “Jon is always protecting Sansa uwu” and I just…no. Jon was not “protecting” Sansa from Theon. He only grabbed him because he was still pissed at him for like…every other reason he would be, it wasn’t because Theon mentioned Sansa or he thought Theon was a threat to Sansa, that’s …literally the opposite of what was going on. The point of that scene isn’t that Jon’s saying “don’t talk about Sansa”, it’s that he’s acknowledging that the only reason he doesn’t  completely despise Theon is because he did something to HELP Sansa. Jon grabbed Littlefinger by the throat because he clearly had creepy intentions towards his sister. He grabbed Theon for entirely different reasons, please stop making it about your ship at Theon’s expense, when he was only showing genuine concern for Sansa.

Oh, and a side note, Theon didn’t choose to rescue Yara because what Jon said gave him the courage to do so. That’s another misconception I see all too often. He was already planning on it from the beginning. The crux of their conversation in 7.07 was something like: “I’ll never forgive myself for betraying your family and I never intend to do it again, but my own family needs me more than yours right now please don’t consider this another betrayal because it isn’t,” with Jon’s response being “yeah i get it go for it.” Theon wanted to clear the air with Jon first because he doesn’t know if he’ll ever see the Starks again. Certainly he wanted  Jon’s blessing for what he was about to do, but he didn’t need it. It might have made him feel better about saving Yara, because he knew the Starks wouldn’t think he was leaving them behind, so he could have no guilt about choosing his own family again, but it was his choice and it was one he made way back in episode 4, and not based on anything Jon told him. I know that isn’t explicitly what’s stated in the scene, but it was always pretty obvious to me. And no, the fact that it isn’t explicitly stated isn’t “just bad writing”, the writers just assume that the viewers have some idea of subtlety and implication in dialogue, which unfortunately based on the online reactions (of this as well as many other scenes) most don’t seem to.

summary: ASOIAF characters + TES deities ❯ Sansa Stark - Mara ❝ Mara teaches that love provides nourishment and life to all mortals. Her...
caption:
ASOIAF characters + TES deities
❯ Sansa Stark - Mara

❝ Mara teaches that love provides nourishment and life to all mortals. Her benevolence is eternal, and those who offer their love to the Divine will never be forsaken. Priests of Mara teach that she is omnipresent and her love and affection can be found in the heart of all mortals. She is also the patron of marriage, and the act of union is carried out at her shrines and temples. It is confirmed upon taking the Pledge of Mara, and she does not place any restrictions on marriage, thus all may marry, irrespective of gender and race, and unite their souls in the holy union.❞

summary: I’m going to be sad if arya and Sansa don’t make it to the end. We stan a murder sister duo
question: I’m going to be sad if arya and Sansa don’t make it to the end. We stan a murder sister duo
answer:
Hey anon,

Oh, I’d be devastated if either died. We’ve followed these young ladies since they were little girls throughout all their trails and tribulations. From their lows to their very, very lows with like three highs in between. After everything that’s happened they deserve to make it to the very end and find some semblance of contentment. Really, all our protagonist do.

I do think that both are relatively safe to reach the end of the series. I don’t see any real benefit to having either of them die. How happy or content either of them will be at the end of the series is a different question. One would hope they’ll be at least okay.
